      <p>
        <add>Yiddish</add>
      </p>
      <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>N. Y.</placeName> Friday, Pericope Tzav<lb/>
        <date>(March) 1854</date>.</p>
      <p>To my friend, etc, <addressee>Yitzchok Isaac Leeser</addressee>:</p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">I let you know that I and my<lb/> family are well and I hope that with you
        my<lb/> friend nothing is lacking. And now, dearest<lb/> friend, I hope you will hear with
        me.<lb/> When I make a suggestion to you which I<lb/> hope you will not take in bad part.
        For<lb/> there is no one who has taken more trouble<lb/> for my sake than you. Therefore,
        first<lb/> of all, “Do not become angry at your<lb/> servant.” I need a dozen wooden<lb/>
        chairs and settee of the best quality,<lb/> light in color and gilded. The settee should
        be<lb/> very wide. You will be good enough to buy it for<lb/> me and the merchant may send
        the bill with it<lb/> or you can pay it for me, and I shall im–<lb/>mediately return the
        money to you by check,<lb/> as well as other money, for Bibles which I<lb/> have received. I
        remain your servant, etc.<lb/>
        <persName role="author">Simon C. Noot</persName>,<lb/> Greene St. between Houston and
        Bleecker Str. </p>
    </body>
  </text>
